Date: Sun 14 Jan 2024
Source: My Republica [edited]
<https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/chitwan-reports-four-scrub-typ=
hus-deaths-with-163-infections-in-current-fy/>


Chitwan has reported 4 deaths from scrub typhus in the current fiscal
year, and of them, one was from within the district and the remaining
3 from outside the district, according to the Health Office, Chitwan.
As said by the Health Office's Vector Control Inspector Ram KC, so far
in the current fiscal year there are 163 confirmed cases of scrub
typhus out of 3254 tests, and among the infected, 4 succumbed to the
disease that is caused by bacterium called _Orientia tsutsugamushi_.
Among the infected, 88 are from Chitwan and the remaining from other
districts.

Last fiscal year, 519 scrub typhus infected were identified through
tests conducted on 3485 people who visited the district-based
hospitals for treatment. All the infected recovered following
treatment.

Scrub typhus bacteria do not directly transmit to humans, but infected
mites, found in vegetation, primarily transmit to other animals and
humans. Severe fever, reddish eyes, coughing, vomiting, stomach pain,
loose bowels, breathing difficulties, joint and muscle pain, skin
rashes, and sometimes the appearance of a black spot at the site of
the bite are among the symptoms of scrub typhus.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[The diagnosis of scrub typhus in Nepal has increased since the 2015
earthquake, with 101 cases of scrub typhus in 2015, 831 cases in 2016,
and 1435 cases in 2017-2018. This had been attributed to people living
in temporary shelters where they might have been exposed to infected
chiggers (larval mites), but some of this increase may be due to
enhanced surveillance for this disease. Rodents may serve as
reservoirs, although transovarial transmission in mites is the
dominant mechanism for maintenance of _O. tsutsugamushi_ in nature.

Scrub typhus presents clinically with chills, fever, headache, muscle
pain, and sometimes with a macular or maculopapular rash and a
necrotic skin lesion at the site of mite inoculation (the eschar).
Other than the eschar, scrub typhus has no distinctive clinical
features to make an accurate clinical diagnosis, and the presence of
an eschar in patients has been reported to vary widely. Confirmation
of the diagnosis requires laboratory testing, usually by indirect
immunofluorescent antibody (IFA) assay, but this will require a 4-fold
rise in antibody titer between acute and convalescent specimens.
Results from a single acute serum sample are unreliable, as it takes
7-10 days for IgG antibody to be detectable, and antibody will be
present in a high percentage of healthy people in an endemic region
such as Nepal.

Doxycycline is the drug of choice, and it is preferred over other
tetracyclines for treatment of scrub typhus; it is rarely associated
with staining of teeth in children younger than 8 years
(<https://doi.org/10.1002/14651858.cd002150.pub2>). Macrolides, such
as azithromycin, are also reported to be efficacious, and
fluoroquinolones, such as ciprofloxacin and ofloxacin, have been
reported to be clinically effective in the treatment of scrub typhus
in a few patients. However, some clinical studies suggest that
fluoroquinolones are not as effective in patients with scrub typhus as
other antimicrobials.

Interestingly, a recent publication in Emerging Infectious Diseases
found _Orientia_ species in North Carolina (references in original
URL):

Chen K, Travanty NV, Garshong R, et al. Detection of _Orientia_ spp.
bacteria in field-collected, free-living _Eutrombicula_ chigger mites,
United States. Emerg Infect Dis. 2023; 29(8): 1676-1679;
<https://doi.org/10.3201/eid2908.230528>.
